Map of Western Eurasia showing the significant genetic flows in the region during the Middle Ages by arrows connecting the respective donor group with the populations recipients of its genetic contribution. The colors of the arrows represent the current national identity of the donors, and the thickness of the arrows represents the share of their genetic influence. The periods of genetic influence related to the indicated donor groups are also shown. During the Middle Ages, the Balkans received the greatest genetic contribution from today's Italy, the Baltics, Ukraine and the Caucasus. During this period, Balkan genes were exported to southern Italy, the northern Black Sea coast, the Caucasus, Anatolia and the northern Caspian Sea.
